      "segment_id": "context",
      "type": "context",
      "audio_script": "John appears after 400 years of prophetic silence, fulfilling Isaiah's prophecy. His ministry prepared Israel for the Messiah through a call to repentance. His message challenged religious assumptions and pointed to One greater than himself."
    },
    {
      "segment_id": "analysis",
      "type": "analysis",
      "audio_script": "John's baptism symbolized cleansing and repentance. Jesus' baptism was different; He had no sin to confess. Instead, He identified with sinners and inaugurated His mission to fulfill all righteousness. The Father's voice and Spirit's descent confirmed His identity."
    },
    {
      "segment_id": "themes",
      "type": "themes",
      "audio_script": "Key themes include prophetic fulfillment, the kingdom's arrival, true repentance bearing fruit, and the Trinity revealed at Jesus' baptism. John models humility, pointing away from himself to Christ."
    },
    {
      "segment_id": "question",
      "type": "question",
      "audio_script": "Reflect on this: How does Jesus' willingness to be baptized show His commitment to identifying with humanity? What does the Father's declaration teach us about Jesus' identity and mission?"
