<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_01.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_01",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 1,
  "title": "Promise and Ascension",
  "objective": "Understand Jesus' final instructions, the promise of the Holy Spirit, and the mission launched from His ascension.",
  "duration": "9 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf04_lesson_12",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_1_1_26",
      "reference": "Acts 1:1-26",
      "text": "In the first book, O Theophilus, I have dealt with all that Jesus began to do and teach... He presented himself alive to them after his suffering by many proofs... He ordered them not to depart from Jerusalem, but to wait for the promise of the Father... 'You will receive power when the Holy Spirit has come upon you, and you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth.' ... he was lifted up, and a cloud took him out of their sight... 'This Jesus... will come in the same way as you saw him go into heaven.' ... they devoted themselves to prayer... Matthias was numbered with the eleven apostles."
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Acts begins the story of Jesus continuing His work through the Spirit-filled church. Today we see the promise, the mission, and the ascension.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 1. Jesus appeared alive after His suffering and taught about the kingdom. He commanded the disciples to wait in Jerusalem for the promise of the Father: 'You will be baptized with the Holy Spirit.' They asked, 'Lord, will you at this time restore the kingdom to Israel?' Jesus replied, 'It is not for you to know times or seasons... but you will receive power when the Holy Spirit has come upon you, and you will be my witnesses... to the end of the earth.' After saying this, He was lifted up, and a cloud took Him out of their sight. Two men in white said, 'This Jesus... will come in the same way.' The disciples returned to Jerusalem and devoted themselves to prayer. Peter led the believers to replace Judas, and Matthias was chosen.",
      "word_count": 137
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "Luke writes Acts as volume two after his Gospel. Jesus has risen and now commissions His people. Acts 1:8 provides the book's outline: Jerusalem, Judea-Samaria, then the nations. The apostles wait in obedience, pray in unity, and prepare leadership.",
      "word_count": 39
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "The ascension is not Jesus' absence but His enthronement. The mission is impossible without the Spirit's power. Waiting is not passivity—it is faithful preparation through prayer and Scripture. Replacing Judas restores apostolic witness to the resurrection and prepares for Pentecost.",
      "word_count": 40
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include Jesus' ongoing reign, Spirit-empowered witness, global mission, prayerful dependence, obedience while waiting, apostolic authority, and hope in Christ's return.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What geographical outline does Jesus give in Acts 1:8 for the spread of the gospel? Answer: Jerusalem, Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth.",
      "correct_answer": "Jerusalem, Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "acts 1:8 — jerusalem then judea and samaria then the whole world",
        "from jerusalem outward to samaria and to the ends of the earth",
        "the three-stage mission: local, regional, worldwide"
      ],
      "word_count": 29
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "Jesus ascends as reigning Lord and sends His church into the world by the Spirit's power. Next, Pentecost ignites the mission.",
      "word_count": 21
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "1",
    "theological_themes": [
      "ascension",
      "holy_spirit",
      "mission",
      "witness",
      "prayer",
      "second_coming"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_30_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "ascension",
      "definition": "Jesus' departure into heaven in Acts 1:9-11; the cloud received him from sight and angels promised his visible return — the ascension begins the era of the Spirit and the church's mission"
    },
    {
      "term": "Acts 1:8 outline",
      "definition": "The geographic program of Acts — Jerusalem (chapters 1-7), Judea and Samaria (8-12), and ends of the earth (13-28); scholars note Rome as Luke's symbol for the empire's extremity"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_02.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_02",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 2,
  "title": "Pentecost Power",
  "objective": "Explore the coming of the Holy Spirit, Peter's sermon, and the birth of the New Testament church.",
  "duration": "10 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_01",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_2_1_47",
      "reference": "Acts 2:1-47",
      "text": "When the day of Pentecost arrived, they were all together in one place... they were all filled with the Holy Spirit and began to speak in other tongues... Peter said, 'This is what was uttered through the prophet Joel'... 'this Jesus... God raised up'... 'Let all the house of Israel therefore know for certain that God has made him both Lord and Christ, this Jesus whom you crucified.' ... 'Repent and be baptized... and you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit.' ... about three thousand souls were added... They devoted themselves to the apostles' teaching and the fellowship, to the breaking of bread and the prayers."
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Pentecost is the decisive outpouring of the Spirit. Today we witness bold proclamation, mass conversion, and the church's foundational practices.",
      "word_count": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 2. On Pentecost, a sound like a mighty rushing wind filled the house, and divided tongues as of fire rested on each of them. They were filled with the Holy Spirit and spoke in other languages. Jews from many nations heard the mighty works of God in their own tongues. Peter stood and explained: this fulfills Joel's prophecy. He proclaimed Jesus' death by lawless men, His resurrection, and exaltation. Peter declared, 'God has made him both Lord and Christ, this Jesus whom you crucified.' The crowd was cut to the heart and asked, 'What shall we do?' Peter answered, 'Repent and be baptized... and you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit.' About three thousand were added. The believers devoted themselves to apostolic teaching, fellowship, breaking bread, and prayers, sharing generously with glad hearts.",
      "word_count": 138
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "Pentecost was a Jewish pilgrimage feast, bringing nations to Jerusalem. God uses this moment to launch global witness. Peter, once fearful, now preaches boldly because the Spirit has come.",
      "word_count": 29
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "Pentecost reverses Babel's confusion by uniting people through the gospel. The Spirit empowers proclamation centered on Jesus' death, resurrection, and lordship. Repentance and baptism publicly mark allegiance to Christ. The church's pattern is theological depth, shared life, worship, and generous love.",
      "word_count": 41
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include Spirit baptism, fulfillment of prophecy, Christ-centered preaching, repentance and baptism, salvation by grace, church formation, devotion to teaching and prayer, and missional community life.",
      "word_count": 27
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What is Peter's answer when the crowd asks what they must do in Acts 2:38? Answer: repent and be baptized, every one of you, in the name of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of your sins, and you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit.",
      "correct_answer": "repent and be baptized in Jesus' name for forgiveness of sins, and receive the Holy Spirit",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "repent, be baptized in Christ's name, receive forgiveness and the holy spirit",
        "acts 2:38 — repentance, baptism, and the gift of the spirit",
        "peter calls for repentance and baptism as response to pentecost"
      ],
      "word_count": 48
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "The Spirit has come, Christ is proclaimed, and the church is born. Next, we see bold witness under opposition in Jerusalem.",
      "word_count": 21
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "2",
    "theological_themes": [
      "pentecost",
      "holy_spirit",
      "repentance",
      "baptism",
      "church",
      "apostolic_preaching"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_30_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "Pentecost",
      "definition": "The Jewish harvest festival fifty days after Passover; Acts 2 records the outpouring of the Holy Spirit with wind, fire, and tongues, fulfilling Joel 2 and Jesus' promise in Acts 1:8"
    },
    {
      "term": "speaking in tongues",
      "definition": "The miraculous speech at Pentecost in Acts 2 where each person heard in their own language; it reverses Babel's confusion and signals the gospel going to all nations"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_03.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_03",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 3,
  "title": "Bold in Jerusalem",
  "objective": "See how the early church proclaims Christ with courage amid miracles, threats, and prayerful dependence.",
  "duration": "9 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_02",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_3_1_4_37",
      "reference": "Acts 3:1-4:37",
      "text": "Peter said, 'In the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, rise up and walk!' ... all the people ran together... Peter preached Jesus' resurrection... 'there is salvation in no one else' ... the council commanded them not to speak... Peter and John answered, 'We cannot but speak of what we have seen and heard.' ... they prayed... 'grant to your servants to continue to speak your word with all boldness' ... they were all filled with the Holy Spirit and continued to speak the word of God with boldness."
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "A healed beggar opens the door for bold gospel witness. Today we see miracle, message, persecution, and united prayer.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 3 and 4. At the temple gate called Beautiful, Peter said to a lame man, 'In the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, rise up and walk.' Immediately he was healed and praised God. Peter preached that this happened by faith in Jesus, whom God raised from the dead. The priests and Sadducees arrested Peter and John, yet many believed. Before the council, Peter declared, 'There is salvation in no one else.' The leaders threatened them not to speak in Jesus' name. Peter and John replied, 'We cannot but speak of what we have seen and heard.' The church prayed for boldness, and the place was shaken. They were filled with the Holy Spirit and spoke God's word boldly, sharing possessions so none were in need.",
      "word_count": 129
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "The apostles minister in Jerusalem's temple context where the same authorities who condemned Jesus now oppose His followers. Healing authenticates proclamation, but the core issue is Jesus' exclusive lordship.",
      "word_count": 29
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "Miracles in Acts are signs pointing to Christ, not ends in themselves. Opposition does not silence the church; it drives prayer. The church asks not for safety but boldness. Spirit filling repeatedly empowers mission. Shared generosity shows the gospel's social fruit.",
      "word_count": 41
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include Jesus' name and power, resurrection witness, exclusive salvation in Christ, courage under threat, prayer for boldness, Spirit empowerment, and sacrificial community.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What is the name Peter gives to the lame man after healing him in Acts 3? Answer: he is healed not in Peter's name but in the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth.",
      "correct_answer": "healed in the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "in the name of jesus christ of nazareth rise and walk",
        "peter heals by the authority of jesus name not his own",
        "acts 3 — silver and gold I have not but in jesus name walk"
      ],
      "word_count": 35
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "The church proclaims Jesus despite pressure. Next, we see internal purity and the first martyr as mission expands.",
      "word_count": 18
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "3-4",
    "theological_themes": [
      "healing",
      "resurrection",
      "exclusive_salvation",
      "persecution",
      "prayer",
      "boldness",
      "community"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_30_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "Beautiful Gate",
      "definition": "The temple entrance where Peter and John healed the lame man in Acts 3; the miracle drew a crowd to the temple courts and provided the occasion for Peter's sermon"
    },
    {
      "term": "Peter's sermon in Acts 3",
      "definition": "Peter's address after the healing attributing the miracle to the glorified Jesus; he calls Israel to repentance and points to the prophets who foretold the Christ's suffering and return"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_04.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_04",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 4,
  "title": "Purity, Service, and Witness",
  "objective": "Understand God's holiness in the church, servant leadership, and Stephen's faithful witness unto death.",
  "duration": "10 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_03",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_5_1_7_60",
      "reference": "Acts 5:1-7:60",
      "text": "Ananias and Sapphira lied to the Holy Spirit... great fear came upon the whole church... the apostles were arrested and released by an angel... 'We must obey God rather than men.' ... seven men were appointed to serve... Stephen, full of grace and power... gave testimony of Israel's history and accused resistance to the Spirit... they stoned Stephen, and he prayed, 'Lord Jesus, receive my spirit' and 'do not hold this sin against them.'"
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Church growth is matched by testing. Today we see God's holiness, wise leadership development, and Stephen's martyrdom.",
      "word_count": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 5 through 7. Ananias and Sapphira lied about their gift, and Peter said they lied to the Holy Spirit; both fell dead, and great fear came upon all. The apostles performed many signs, were arrested, and an angel released them to keep preaching. Before the council they declared, 'We must obey God rather than men.' Gamaliel advised caution. As disciples increased, a complaint arose over neglected widows. The apostles appointed seven Spirit-filled servants, including Stephen. Stephen performed signs and was seized. In his speech, he retold Israel's history, showing repeated rejection of God's messengers and culminating in rejection of the Righteous One. Enraged leaders stoned him. Stephen saw Jesus standing at God's right hand and prayed for mercy on his killers as he died.",
      "word_count": 127
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "Rapid growth brings both external persecution and internal challenges. Luke shows that Spirit-filled leadership includes both word ministry and practical care. Stephen's speech reframes temple-centered religion around Jesus as the true fulfillment.",
      "word_count": 32
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "Holiness matters in gospel community; hypocrisy is not trivial. The apostles prioritize prayer and word while empowering others to serve, creating healthy ministry structure. Stephen models scriptural faithfulness and Christlike forgiveness at death. His martyrdom becomes a turning point that scatters believers for mission.",
      "word_count": 44
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include holiness before God, honesty in community, obedience above human authority, shared leadership, Spirit-filled service, biblical theology of fulfillment in Christ, martyr witness, and forgiving enemies.",
      "word_count": 28
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: Why did Ananias and Sapphira die in Acts 5? Answer: they lied to the Holy Spirit by keeping back part of the money from a land sale while pretending to give the full amount.",
      "correct_answer": "they lied to the Holy Spirit by claiming to give all while secretly keeping part",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "they deceived the holy spirit about the proceeds of their land",
        "ananias and sapphira kept part of the sale price but pretended to give all — they lied to god",
        "acts 5 — deceit before god about the offering amount"
      ],
      "word_count": 36
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "God purifies and strengthens His church through testing. Next, the gospel moves beyond Jerusalem through persecution and conversion.",
      "word_count": 18
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "5-7",
    "theological_themes": [
      "holiness",
      "church_discipline",
      "leadership",
      "service",
      "martyrdom",
      "forgiveness",
      "obedience"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_31_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "Ananias and Sapphira",
      "definition": "The couple in Acts 5 who died for lying to the Holy Spirit about their offering; their story follows the generosity of Barnabas and establishes the seriousness of hypocrisy in the community"
    },
    {
      "term": "Stephen",
      "definition": "The first Christian martyr in Acts 7 whose speech before the Sanhedrin traced Israel's history of rejecting God's messengers; his stoning introduced Saul of Tarsus and scattered the Jerusalem church outward"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_05.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_05",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 5,
  "title": "From Persecutor to Preacher",
  "objective": "Trace gospel expansion to Samaria, the Ethiopian official's conversion, and Saul's dramatic transformation.",
  "duration": "10 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_04",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_8_1_9_43",
      "reference": "Acts 8:1-9:43",
      "text": "There arose a great persecution... those scattered went about preaching the word... Philip proclaimed Christ in Samaria... Simon believed outwardly but his heart was not right... an angel sent Philip to the Ethiopian eunuch reading Isaiah; he preached Jesus and baptized him... Saul, still breathing threats, met the risen Jesus on the road to Damascus... 'he is a chosen instrument of mine' ... Saul proclaimed Jesus in synagogues... the church had peace and was built up."
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Persecution scatters believers, but the gospel spreads. Today we see mission in Samaria and the astonishing conversion of Saul.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 8 and 9. After Stephen's death, great persecution scattered the church, and those scattered preached the word. Philip proclaimed Christ in Samaria with joy and signs. Peter confronted Simon's false heart. An angel then sent Philip to a desert road where an Ethiopian official read Isaiah. Beginning with that Scripture, Philip told him the good news about Jesus. The official believed and was baptized. Meanwhile Saul sought to destroy the church. On the road to Damascus, a light from heaven flashed and a voice said, 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?' Saul asked, 'Who are you, Lord?' The answer came, 'I am Jesus.' Blinded, Saul was led into the city. The Lord sent Ananias to him, saying Saul was a chosen instrument. Saul was filled with the Spirit, baptized, and immediately proclaimed Jesus as the Son of God.",
      "word_count": 142
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "Acts 1:8 unfolds: from Jerusalem to Samaria and beyond. The Ethiopian likely represents the gospel reaching the nations. Saul's conversion prepares the future apostle to the Gentiles.",
      "word_count": 27
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "Persecution cannot stop mission; God uses it to spread witness. Scripture-centered evangelism leads the Ethiopian to Christ. True conversion changes allegiance and life, unlike superficial belief. Saul's conversion shows grace is stronger than hostility; the church's greatest enemy becomes its greatest missionary theologian.",
      "word_count": 43
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include providence in persecution, cross-cultural mission, Scripture and Christ-centered evangelism, authentic repentance, calling, and transforming grace.",
      "word_count": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What did Jesus say to Saul on the Damascus road when Saul asked who was speaking? Answer: I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting.",
      "correct_answer": "I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "I am Jesus whom you persecute",
        "the voice said I am Jesus — confronting saul on the road to damascus",
        "acts 9 — jesus identifies himself to the persecutor saul"
      ],
      "word_count": 26
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "The gospel reaches new peoples and transforms Saul. Next, God opens the door to Gentiles through Peter and Cornelius.",
      "word_count": 19
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "8-9",
    "theological_themes": [
      "persecution",
      "samaria",
      "evangelism",
      "conversion",
      "calling",
      "grace",
      "missions"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_32_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "Damascus road",
      "definition": "The location of Saul's conversion in Acts 9; blinded by a light from heaven, Saul fell and heard Jesus identify himself — transforming the chief persecutor into the apostle to the Gentiles"
    },
    {
      "term": "Philip the evangelist",
      "definition": "One of the seven deacons who preached in Samaria and explained Isaiah 53 to the Ethiopian eunuch in Acts 8; his ministry shows the gospel crossing ethnic and geographic boundaries"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_06.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_06",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 6,
  "title": "One Gospel for All",
  "objective": "See how God welcomes Gentiles through Cornelius and how the church discerns the Spirit's work among all peoples.",
  "duration": "10 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_05",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_10_1_12_25",
      "reference": "Acts 10:1-12:25",
      "text": "Cornelius, a centurion... saw an angel... Peter saw a vision of unclean animals and heard, 'What God has made clean, do not call common.' ... Peter preached Jesus in Cornelius's house... 'everyone who believes in him receives forgiveness of sins through his name.' ... the Holy Spirit fell on all who heard... they were baptized... the Jerusalem believers glorified God: 'Then to the Gentiles also God has granted repentance that leads to life.' ... the church in Antioch grew... Barnabas brought Saul... disciples were first called Christians... Herod executed James and imprisoned Peter; God delivered Peter by an angel."
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "A major turning point arrives: Gentiles receive the same gospel and Spirit. Today we watch barriers fall and the church become visibly multiethnic.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 10 through 12. Cornelius, a God-fearing centurion, received an angelic message to send for Peter. Meanwhile Peter saw a vision and heard, 'What God has made clean, do not call common.' In Cornelius's house Peter proclaimed Jesus—His life, death, and resurrection—and declared that everyone who believes receives forgiveness through His name. While Peter spoke, the Holy Spirit fell on the Gentiles, and they praised God. Peter commanded they be baptized. Back in Jerusalem, Peter explained the Spirit's work, and the believers glorified God for granting Gentiles repentance unto life. In Antioch many believed; Barnabas and Saul taught there, and disciples were first called Christians. Herod killed James, jailed Peter, but God delivered Peter by an angel as the church prayed earnestly.",
      "word_count": 124
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "Jew-Gentile separation shaped first-century identity. God directly intervenes through visions and Spirit outpouring to show full inclusion of Gentiles in Christ. Antioch emerges as a strategic mission center.",
      "word_count": 28
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "God shows no partiality: salvation is by faith in Jesus for all peoples. The same Spirit, same gospel, and same baptism mark equal belonging. The church must adjust tradition to God's revealed mission. Prayer remains central amid persecution.",
      "word_count": 38
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include impartial grace, Gentile inclusion, Spirit confirmation, repentance unto life, church discernment, Antioch mission culture, persecution, and deliverance through prayer.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What did Peter's vision of the unclean animals in Acts 10 teach him? Answer: do not call anything impure that God has made clean — the vision prepared him to accept Cornelius, a Gentile.",
      "correct_answer": "do not call anything impure that God has made clean — applied to accepting Gentiles",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "god has made clean what you call impure — the vision prepared peter for cornelius",
        "the vision overturned food laws as a sign that no person should be called unclean",
        "acts 10 — the sheet vision meant gentiles are not to be excluded"
      ],
      "word_count": 36
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "God opens the door wide to the nations. Next, Paul and Barnabas are sent as missionaries from Antioch.",
      "word_count": 18
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "10-12",
    "theological_themes": [
      "gentile_inclusion",
      "holy_spirit",
      "forgiveness",
      "unity",
      "antioch",
      "prayer",
      "persecution"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_41_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "Cornelius",
      "definition": "The Roman centurion in Acts 10 whose household received the Holy Spirit before baptism; Peter's visit to him and the Spirit's outpouring convinced the Jerusalem church that God had accepted Gentiles"
    },
    {
      "term": "Jerusalem Council",
      "definition": "The gathering in Acts 15 that decided Gentile believers did not need to be circumcised; it established that salvation is by grace alone through faith — the first major doctrinal decision of the church"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_07.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_07",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 7,
  "title": "Sent from Antioch",
  "objective": "Follow Paul and Barnabas on the first missionary journey and see the gospel spread through proclamation and suffering.",
  "duration": "9 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_06",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_13_1_14_28",
      "reference": "Acts 13:1-14:28",
      "text": "The Holy Spirit said, 'Set apart for me Barnabas and Saul...' ... in Pisidian Antioch Paul preached redemptive history fulfilled in Jesus... many Gentiles rejoiced... Jews stirred persecution... in Lystra Paul was stoned... they strengthened the disciples, saying, 'through many tribulations we must enter the kingdom of God.'"
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Mission now moves intentionally from Antioch. Today we follow the first missionary journey and its mix of fruit and suffering.",
      "word_count": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 13 and 14. In Antioch, while the church worshiped and fasted, the Holy Spirit said, 'Set apart for me Barnabas and Saul.' They preached in Cyprus and then in Pisidian Antioch, where Paul proclaimed Jesus as David's promised Savior raised from the dead. Many believed, especially Gentiles, but opposition grew. In Iconium and Lystra, God confirmed the word with signs. After healing a crippled man, crowds tried to worship Paul and Barnabas as gods, but they redirected glory to the living Creator. Soon opponents stoned Paul and left him for dead, yet he rose and continued. They revisited cities to strengthen disciples and appoint elders in every church.",
      "word_count": 111
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "This journey establishes Paul's pattern: synagogue first, then Gentile mission. New churches are planted with local leadership, not dependence on traveling apostles.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "Mission is Spirit-initiated, church-sent, Scripture-preached, and suffering-enduring. Success is measured by faithful witness and mature disciples, not comfort. Appointing elders shows long-term church health matters from the start.",
      "word_count": 28
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include Spirit-led sending, gospel proclamation, Gentile joy, persecution, perseverance, discipleship, and eldership formation.",
      "word_count": 15
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What happened when Paul and Barnabas were sent out from Antioch in Acts 13? Answer: the Holy Spirit directed the church to set them apart and send them; they were commissioned by prayer and laying on of hands.",
      "correct_answer": "the Holy Spirit commanded them to set apart Paul and Barnabas for mission; the church prayed and sent them",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "the spirit said set apart paul and barnabas for the work — the church prayed and sent them",
        "acts 13 — spirit-directed commissioning of the first missionary journey from antioch",
        "the antioch church fasted, prayed, laid hands on them and sent them"
      ],
      "word_count": 40
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "The gospel advances through Spirit-led courage. Next, the Jerusalem Council clarifies salvation by grace for all believers.",
      "word_count": 17
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "13-14",
    "theological_themes": [
      "missionary_journey",
      "spirit_sending",
      "church_planting",
      "perseverance",
      "elders"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_46_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "first missionary journey",
      "definition": "Paul and Barnabas's mission in Acts 13-14 through Cyprus, Pisidian Antioch, Iconium, Lystra, and Derbe; they established churches and returned to Antioch before the Jerusalem Council"
    },
    {
      "term": "Antioch",
      "definition": "The Syrian city where disciples were first called Christians; it became the mission base for Paul's three journeys and modeled a multiethnic community led by prophets and teachers"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_08.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_08",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 8,
  "title": "Grace and Guidance",
  "objective": "Understand the Jerusalem Council and the second journey where God redirects mission into Macedonia.",
  "duration": "10 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_07",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_15_1_16_40",
      "reference": "Acts 15:1-16:40",
      "text": "Some taught, 'Unless you are circumcised... you cannot be saved.' ... Peter said, 'we believe that we will be saved through the grace of the Lord Jesus.' ... the council sent a letter... Paul received a vision, 'Come over to Macedonia and help us.' ... Lydia believed... Paul and Silas were imprisoned and sang hymns... an earthquake opened doors... the jailer asked, 'What must I do to be saved?' They said, 'Believe in the Lord Jesus.'"
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "A doctrinal crisis and a missionary redirection shape the church's future. Today we see salvation by grace defended and mission crossing into Europe.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 15 and 16. In Jerusalem, some demanded circumcision for salvation. Peter testified that God gave Gentiles the Spirit by faith, and said, 'We will be saved through the grace of the Lord Jesus.' James affirmed this from Scripture. The council sent a letter to Gentile believers clarifying essentials for fellowship, not a works-based gospel. Paul began a new journey with Silas. The Spirit prevented certain routes, then in a vision a man from Macedonia called for help. In Philippi, Lydia believed and opened her home. After Paul cast out a spirit from a slave girl, Paul and Silas were beaten and jailed. At midnight they prayed and sang. An earthquake opened doors, yet they stayed. The jailer asked, 'What must I do to be saved?' They answered, 'Believe in the Lord Jesus.' He and his household were baptized.",
      "word_count": 141
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "The Jerusalem Council protects gospel clarity and church unity. The Macedonian call marks a major geographic expansion into Europe.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "The gospel is grace alone through faith, not ethnic boundary markers or law-keeping. Unity requires truth and love. Mission guidance is often directional through closed and open doors. Joyful worship in suffering becomes a powerful witness.",
      "word_count": 36
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include justification by grace, doctrinal discernment, unity across cultures, Spirit guidance, worship in suffering, household conversions, and mission expansion.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What did the Jerusalem Council decide about circumcision and Gentile believers in Acts 15? Answer: Gentile believers are not required to be circumcised; they need only abstain from food sacrificed to idols, blood, strangled animals, and sexual immorality.",
      "correct_answer": "Gentiles need not be circumcised; they should only abstain from idols, blood, strangled meat, and sexual immorality",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "no circumcision required for gentiles — james announced four abstentions only",
        "acts 15 council: grace alone — four minimal requirements for table fellowship",
        "the decree from jerusalem: gentiles accepted without circumcision"
      ],
      "word_count": 40
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "The church stands firm on grace and follows God's guidance into new fields. Next, Paul reasons in key cities and forms strategic churches.",
      "word_count": 23
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "15-16",
    "theological_themes": [
      "grace",
      "jerusalem_council",
      "justification",
      "spirit_guidance",
      "suffering",
      "mission"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_49_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "circumcision party",
      "definition": "Jewish believers who insisted Gentile converts must be circumcised and keep the Mosaic law; their position prompted the Jerusalem Council and is refuted in Acts 15 and Galatians"
    },
    {
      "term": "Paul and Silas",
      "definition": "The missionary pair in Acts 15-18 after Paul and Barnabas separated; Silas joined Paul for the second journey through Macedonia, Philippi, Thessalonica, Berea, Athens, and Corinth"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_09.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_09",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 9,
  "title": "Reasoning in the Cities",
  "objective": "Track Paul's witness in Thessalonica, Berea, Athens, and Corinth, learning contextual mission without compromising truth.",
  "duration": "9 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_08",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_17_1_18_28",
      "reference": "Acts 17:1-18:28",
      "text": "Paul reasoned from the Scriptures that the Christ had to suffer and rise... Bereans examined the Scriptures daily... in Athens Paul proclaimed the unknown God who commands all people everywhere to repent... in Corinth the Lord said, 'Do not be afraid... I have many in this city who are my people.' ... Apollos was instructed more accurately by Priscilla and Aquila."
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Paul engages diverse cultures and worldviews while staying centered on Christ. Today we follow his urban mission strategy.",
      "word_count": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 17 and 18. In Thessalonica, Paul reasoned from the Scriptures that the Messiah had to suffer and rise, and that Jesus is this Messiah. Some believed; others stirred riots. In Berea, people received the word eagerly and examined the Scriptures daily. In Athens, troubled by idolatry, Paul addressed the Areopagus, proclaiming the Creator God and calling all people to repent because God has appointed a man to judge the world, giving assurance by raising Him from the dead. Some mocked, some delayed, some believed. In Corinth, Paul labored and taught for many months. The Lord encouraged him in a vision: 'Do not be afraid... I have many in this city who are my people.' Later, Apollos powerfully taught, and Priscilla and Aquila helped him understand the way more accurately.",
      "word_count": 132
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "These cities represent religious, philosophical, and commercial centers. The gospel speaks into each context without losing doctrinal clarity.",
      "word_count": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "Paul adapts approach, not message. In synagogues he argues from Scripture; among pagans he starts with creation and conscience. The resurrection remains central. Disciple-making includes ongoing correction and equipping, as seen with Apollos.",
      "word_count": 33
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include scriptural reasoning, discernment, contextual apologetics, repentance, resurrection proclamation, courage in mission, and collaborative discipleship.",
      "word_count": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What did Paul say when the Athenians wanted to know about the unknown god in Acts 17? Answer: Paul declared him — the God who made the world and everything in it, Lord of heaven and earth, who gives all people life and breath.",
      "correct_answer": "the God who made the world and everything in it — Lord of heaven and earth who gives all life",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "paul revealed the unknown god as creator of all who gives life to all people",
        "acts 17 — the god who made everything does not live in temples made by hands",
        "the god behind the unknown altar is the creator and sustainer of all things"
      ],
      "word_count": 46
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "The gospel speaks truth in every culture. Next, we watch deep ministry in Ephesus and Paul's farewell to elders.",
      "word_count": 19
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "17-18",
    "theological_themes": [
      "apologetics",
      "contextualization",
      "resurrection",
      "repentance",
      "discipleship",
      "church_planting"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_50_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "Areopagus speech",
      "definition": "Paul's address to Athenian philosophers in Acts 17:22-31; he begins with their altar to an unknown god and proclaims the creator God, resurrection, and coming judgment — meeting his audience on their own ground"
    },
    {
      "term": "Bereans",
      "definition": "The Jews in Acts 17:11 who received Paul's message with eagerness and examined the Scriptures daily to verify his claims; held as a model of noble, critical engagement with preaching"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_10.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_10",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 10,
  "title": "Word and Tears",
  "objective": "Study Paul's Ephesian ministry, spiritual confrontation, and his shepherding farewell to the Ephesian elders.",
  "duration": "10 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_09",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_19_1_20_38",
      "reference": "Acts 19:1-20:38",
      "text": "In Ephesus, disciples received fuller teaching and the Spirit's work... God did extraordinary miracles through Paul... many burned magic books... a riot erupted over Artemis worship... Paul told elders, 'I did not shrink from declaring to you the whole counsel of God' ... 'pay careful attention... to care for the church of God' ... 'It is more blessed to give than to receive.'"
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Ephesus shows the gospel confronting spiritual darkness, economic idols, and leadership challenges. Today we also hear Paul's pastoral heart.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 19 and 20. In Ephesus, Paul taught powerfully for years, and the word spread widely. God worked extraordinary miracles, and many who practiced magic confessed and burned their costly books, showing true repentance. As many turned from idols, merchants tied to Artemis worship incited a city riot. Later, Paul gathered Ephesian elders and reminded them of his tears, trials, and faithful teaching in public and house to house. He testified to repentance toward God and faith in Jesus. He declared, 'I did not shrink from declaring to you the whole counsel of God.' He warned of fierce wolves and urged vigilance: 'Pay careful attention... to care for the church of God.' He commended them to God and the word of His grace.",
      "word_count": 125
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "Ephesus was a major religious and trade center. Gospel conversion threatened idolatrous systems. Paul's farewell speech is the New Testament's clearest pastoral leadership charge in narrative form.",
      "word_count": 27
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "The gospel challenges both personal sin and public idols. Genuine repentance is costly and visible. Healthy leadership requires doctrinal fidelity, emotional investment, sacrificial integrity, and vigilance against false teaching. Ministry is both truth and tears.",
      "word_count": 35
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include repentance from idolatry, spiritual power under Christ, whole-counsel teaching, elder responsibility, church protection, grace, and generous service.",
      "word_count": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What did Paul tell the Ephesian elders was the task he had received from the Lord Jesus in Acts 20? Answer: to testify to the gospel of God's grace.",
      "correct_answer": "to testify to the gospel of God's grace",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "to finish the task of testifying to the gospel of grace",
        "acts 20 — paul says his life's work is witnessing to god's grace",
        "the task given by jesus — bear witness to the gospel of grace"
      ],
      "word_count": 31
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "The word grows where repentance is real and leadership is faithful. Next, Paul heads to Jerusalem under warning and suffering.",
      "word_count": 20
    }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "difficulty": "intermediate",
    "testament": "new",
    "book": "acts",
    "chapter_range": "19-20",
    "theological_themes": [
      "repentance",
      "idolatry",
      "leadership",
      "whole_counsel",
      "church_care",
      "grace"
    ],
    "time_period": "circa_54_ad",
    "canonical_order": 44
  },
  "vocabulary": [
    {
      "term": "Ephesus",
      "definition": "The major city where Paul spent three years in Acts 19-20; the gospel's advance there disrupted the silversmiths who made shrines for Artemis, illustrating the social and economic impact of the gospel"
    },
    {
      "term": "farewell to Ephesian elders",
      "definition": "Paul's speech in Acts 20:17-38 — the only speech addressed to Christians in Acts; he commissions the elders to guard the flock from wolves and commends them to God and the word of his grace"
    }
  ]
}
</file>

<file path="curriculum/courses/new-testament-foundations-05-acts/lessons/ntf05_lesson_11.json">
{
  "lesson_id": "ntf05_lesson_11",
  "course_id": "new_testament_foundations_05_acts",
  "sequence": 11,
  "title": "Witness in Chains",
  "objective": "Follow Paul's arrest in Jerusalem and his bold testimony before hostile crowds and rulers.",
  "duration": "9 minutes",
  "prerequisite": "ntf05_lesson_10",
  "required_passages": [
    {
      "passage_id": "act_21_1_23_35",
      "reference": "Acts 21:1-23:35",
      "text": "Paul went to Jerusalem despite warnings... he was seized in the temple... gave testimony of his conversion... before the council he declared hope in the resurrection... the Lord stood by him and said, 'Take courage, for as you have testified in Jerusalem, so you must bear witness also in Rome.'"
    }
  ],
  "segments": [
    {
      "type": "orientation",
      "sequence": 1,
      "audio_script": "Paul enters Jerusalem knowing suffering awaits. Today we see courageous testimony under arrest and Christ's personal encouragement.",
      "word_count": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "reading",
      "sequence": 2,
      "audio_script": "Listen to Acts 21 through 23. Though warned repeatedly, Paul went to Jerusalem in obedience. False accusations led to a temple riot, and Roman soldiers arrested him. Paul addressed the crowd, recounting his conversion and commission from Jesus to the Gentiles. The crowd erupted, and he was taken into custody. Before the council, Paul declared he was on trial for the hope and resurrection of the dead, dividing Pharisees and Sadducees. A plot formed to kill him, but Paul's nephew reported it. Roman authorities transferred Paul under heavy guard to Caesarea. That night the Lord stood by Paul and said, 'Take courage... you must bear witness also in Rome.'",
      "word_count": 109
    },
    {
      "type": "context",
      "sequence": 3,
      "audio_script": "Jerusalem remains a flashpoint for tensions around law, temple, and Gentile mission. Acts shifts from itinerant missions to courtroom witness under imperial structures.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "type": "analysis",
      "sequence": 4,
      "audio_script": "Faithfulness may require entering danger with clear conscience. Paul uses every legal and rhetorical opening to testify to Christ. Resurrection remains central to Christian hope and defense. Jesus' promise of Rome reframes imprisonment as mission, not defeat.",
      "word_count": 37
    },
    {
      "type": "themes",
      "sequence": 5,
      "audio_script": "Key themes include obedience under warning, testimony in hostility, resurrection hope, divine providence, legal witness, and courage from Christ's presence.",
      "word_count": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "question",
      "sequence": 6,
      "audio_script": "Review question: What was Paul's defense before Felix in Acts 24? Answer: Paul denied all charges of stirring up trouble and affirmed he believed everything written in the Law and Prophets, hoping in the resurrection of both just and unjust.",
      "correct_answer": "Paul denied trouble-making and affirmed belief in resurrection and the Law and Prophets",
      "acceptable_variants": [
        "paul denied the charges and declared his hope in resurrection from the dead",
        "he worshipped the God of his ancestors and believed the prophets and resurrection",
        "acts 24 — paul's defense: fulfillment of the jewish hope including resurrection"
      ],
      "word_count": 40
    },
    {
      "type": "close",
      "sequence": 7,
      "audio_script": "Paul is bound but not silenced. Next, we conclude Acts with trials, storm, and gospel witness in Rome.",
